### Introduction

 As humans, we inherit evolutionary conditioning that developed over millions of years.  
To navigate the complex world around us, our brains have to make fast decisions on incomplete data. We have evolved heuristics—or shortcuts—for making decisions, for everything from the way we process information to the way we relate to others around us. These heuristics developed for an evolutionary purpose: usually to keep us alive, healthy, and reproducing.

But those heuristics don’t always work in our favor. In situations where they lead us astray, the heuristics become cognitive biases, which can easily be manipulated and exploited.  
Each and every human lives with a brain that is subject to these forces. So, technology that takes advantage of these heuristics affects everyone. This is why humane technology is so important. Instead of exploiting these biases for short-term profits, humane technology uses them as design constraints for wise choices. 

When we discuss risks tied to artificial intelligence we often fear the moment when machines become smarter than us: the moment when they overwhelm human strengths. But there is an earlier moment—one we’ve already passed—when artificial intelligence overwhelms human weaknesses.

